\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For some real matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, the following vectors form a basis for its column space and null space:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C(A)=\operatorname{span}\langle\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
1
\end{array}\right),\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
-1
\end{array}\right)\rangle,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N(A)=\operatorname{span}\langle\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
-1\\
0\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right),\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
0\\
0\\
1
\end{array}\right),\left(\begin{array}{c}
2\\
1\\
-1\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right)\rangle.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
What is the size 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, what is its rank, and what are the dimensions of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(A^{T})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N(A^{T}$
\end_inset

)?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Solution:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 must be a 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times5$
\end_inset

 matrix of rank 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 (the dimension of the column space).
 
\begin_inset Formula $C(A^{T})$
\end_inset

 must have the same dimension 2, and 
\begin_inset Formula $N(A^{T})$
\end_inset

 must have dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $3-2=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Give 
\emph on
one
\emph default
 possible matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 with this 
\begin_inset Formula $C(A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N(A)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Solution:
\series default
 We have to make all the columns out of the two 
\begin_inset Formula $C(A)$
\end_inset

 vectors.
 Let's make the first column 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 From the first nullspace vector, the second column must then be 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,0,1)$
\end_inset

; from the second nullspace vector, the fifth column must be 
\begin_inset Formula $(-2,0,-2)$
\end_inset

; from the third nullspace vector, the third column must be 
\begin_inset Formula $(3,0,3)$
\end_inset

.
 The fourth column must be independent and give us the other 
\begin_inset Formula $C(A)$
\end_inset

 vector, so we can just make it 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,1,-1)$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, our 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 matrix is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left(\begin{array}{ccccc}
1 & 1 & 3 & 1 & -2\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 1 & 3 & -1 & -2
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Of course, there are many other possible solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Give a right-hand side 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b$
\end_inset

 has a solution, and give 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for your 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 from the previous part.
 (Hint: you should not have to do Gaussian elimination.)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Solution:
\series default
 we just need 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 to be in the column space, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b=(1,0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 Then a particular solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,0,0,0,0)$
\end_inset

, and to get all possible solutions we just need to add any multiples of
 the nullspace vectors:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
0\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right)+c_{1}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
-1\\
0\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right)+c_{2}\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
1\\
0\\
0\\
1
\end{array}\right)+c_{3}\left(\begin{array}{c}
2\\
1\\
-1\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

for any scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2},c_{3}.$
\end_inset

 (Again, there are many possible solutions to this part.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\left(\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

, the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b$
\end_inset

 as 
\emph on
no solutions
\emph default
.
 Instead, give another right-hand side 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $A\hat{x}=\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 is solvable and yields a least-square solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 minimizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert Ax-b\Vert$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}$
\end_inset

 must be the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
rule[-2pt]{5cm}{0.5pt}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 onto the subspace 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
rule[-2pt]{3cm}{0.5pt}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 (Hint: if you find yourself solving a 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 system of equations, you are missing a way to do it much more easily.
 The answer should 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 depend on your choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 matrix in part b.)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Solution:
\series default
 We just need to project 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $C(A)$
\end_inset

.
 If you look closely, you'll notice that the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $C(A)$
\end_inset

 given above is actually orthogonal (but not orthonormal), so the orthogonal
 projection is easy.
 If we call the two basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

, then the projection is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{b}=\frac{a_{1}a_{1}^{T}}{a_{1}^{T}a_{1}}b+\frac{a_{2}a_{2}^{T}}{a_{2}^{T}a_{2}}b=a_{1}\frac{1}{2}+a_{2}\frac{1}{3}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
5/6\\
1/3\\
1/6
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

We could also have used the projection formula 
\begin_inset Formula $Pb$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\hat{A}(\hat{A}^{T}\hat{A})^{-1}\hat{A}^{T}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
a_{1} & a_{2}\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1\\
0 & 1\\
1 & -1
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This is pretty easy, too, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}^{T}\hat{A}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
2 & 0\\
0 & 3
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

, making it easy to invert (it is diagonal because the basis is orthogonal).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 2:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose you have 100 data points 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{i},y_{i})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,\ldots,100$
\end_inset

, and you want to fit them to a power-law curve 
\begin_inset Formula $y(x)=ax^{b}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, you want to fit 
\begin_inset Formula $\log y_{i}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\log y=\log(ax^{b})=b\log x+\log a$
\end_inset

.
 Describe how to find 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 to 
\emph on
minimize the sum of the squares of the errors:
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s(a,b)=\sum_{i=1}^{100}\left(b\log x_{i}+\log a-\log y_{i}\right)^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Write down a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 system of equations for the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\left(\begin{array}{c}
b\\
\log a
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

; you can leave your equations in the form of a product of matrices/vectors
 as long as you say what the matrices/vectors are.
 (Hint: rewrite it as an 18.06-style least-squares problem with matrices/vectors.)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Solution: 
\series default
In linear-algebra form, we write 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\Vert Az-b\Vert^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $100\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\log x_{1} & 1\\
\log x_{2} & 1\\
\vdots & \vdots\\
\log x_{100} & 1
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $100$
\end_inset

-component vector
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
b=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\log y_{1}\\
\log y_{2}\\
\vdots\\
\log y_{100}
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Then minimizing 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is just an ordinary least-squares problem, and the solution is given by
 the normal equations 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}Az=A^{T}b$
\end_inset

, which is a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 system of equations.
\end_layout

