Problem 3:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 real matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
a_{1} & a_{2} & a_{3} & a_{4}\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 has four 
\emph on
orthogonal 
\emph default
but 
\emph on
not orthonormal 
\emph default
columns 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 with lengths 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert a_{1}\Vert=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert a_{2}\Vert=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert a_{3}\Vert=3$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert a_{4}\Vert=2$
\end_inset

.
 (That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}^{T}a_{j}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\ne j$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Write an explicit expression for the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b$
\end_inset

 in terms of dot products, additions, and multiplications by scalars.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Solution
\series default
: All we are doing is writing 
\begin_inset Formula $b=a_{1}x_{1}+a_{2}x_{2}+a_{3}x_{3}+a_{4}x_{4}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 we are writing 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in the basis of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Since this is an orthogonal basis, we have seen many times in class that
 we just need to take dot products: 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}^{T}b=a_{i}^{T}a_{i}x_{i}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,3,4$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=a_{i}^{T}b/a_{i}^{T}a_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{1}^{T}b/a_{1}^{T}a_{1}\\
a_{2}^{T}b/a_{2}^{T}a_{2}\\
a_{3}^{T}b/a_{3}^{T}a_{3}\\
a_{4}^{T}b/a_{4}^{T}a_{4}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
a_{1}^{T}b/4\\
a_{2}^{T}b\\
a_{3}^{T}b/9\\
a_{4}^{T}b/4
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Equivalently, since 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{T}A$
\end_inset

 is the diagonal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $D=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
a_{1}^{T}a_{1}\\
 & a_{2}^{T}a_{2}\\
 &  & a_{3}^{T}a_{3}\\
 &  &  & a_{4}^{T}a_{4}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
4\\
 & 1\\
 &  & 9\\
 &  &  & 4
\end{array}\right),$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{-1}A^{T}A=I$
\end_inset

, which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{-1}=D^{-1}A^{T}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x=D^{-1}A^{T}b$
\end_inset

.
 If you write it out, this is essentially the same as the answer above (note
 that inverting a diagonal matrix is easy).
 
\end_layout

