\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Solution:
\series default
 The purpose of Gaussian elimination is to factorize 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into a product of triangular matrices, but this 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
already
\emph default
 factorized into a product of triangular matrices.
 So, we just need to do one back-substitution and one forward-substitution
 step.
 In particular, since 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=b=BCx$
\end_inset

, we let 
\begin_inset Formula $Cx=y$
\end_inset

 and first solve 
\begin_inset Formula $By=b$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 by forward substitution (since 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is upper triangular) and then solve 
\begin_inset Formula $Cx=y$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 by backsubstitution.
 To solve 
\begin_inset Formula $By=b$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1\\
3 & 2\\
1 & -1 & 2
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
y_{1}\\
y_{2}\\
y_{3}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
2\\
4\\
7
\end{array}\right)\implies y_{1}=2\implies\begin{array}{c}
3y_{1}+2y_{2}=4\\
\implies y_{2}=-1
\end{array}\implies\begin{array}{c}
y_{1}-y_{2}+2y_{3}=7\\
\implies y_{3}=2
\end{array}.
\]

\end_inset

Now that we know 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(2,-1,2)$
\end_inset

, we solve 
\begin_inset Formula $Cx=y$
\end_inset

 by backsubstitution: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 3 & 1\\
 & 2 & -1\\
 &  & 2
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
x_{1}\\
x_{2}\\
x_{3}
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
2\\
-1\\
2
\end{array}\right)\implies x_{3}=1\implies\begin{array}{c}
2x_{2}-x_{3}=-1\\
\implies x_{2}=0
\end{array}\implies\begin{array}{c}
x_{1}+3x_{2}+x_{3}=2\\
\implies x_{1}=1
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

and hence the solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(1,0,1)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

