\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{n}=\sum_{i}\left[\frac{1-\lambda_{i}}{1+\lambda_{i}}\right]^{n}c_{i}v_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

 But 
\series bold
each of these terms is decaying
\series default
: 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}>0$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is positive-definite), so 
\begin_inset Formula $|1-\lambda|<|1+\lambda|$
\end_inset

 and the ratio has 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\frac{1-\lambda_{i}}{1+\lambda_{i}}\right|<1$
\end_inset

.
 So, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert x_{n}\Vert\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 and the eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}=0.1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{3}=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{4}=3$
\end_inset

, and the corresponding eigenvectors are 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{3}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{4}$
\end_inset

 (all normalized to length 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert v_{k}\Vert=1$
\end_inset

).
 The initial 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 is some arbitrary vector.
 Write an exact formula for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and these eigenvectors and eigenvalues—you should get a sum of four terms.
 Which term should typically dominate for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Solution: 
\series default
As above, but we can furthermore use the fact that the eigenvectors are
 orthonormal (they are orthogonal since it is a real-symmetric matrix with
 distinct eigenvalues, and we normalized them to length 1) to say that the
 coefficients are 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}=v_{i}^{T}x_{0}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{n}=\sum_{i=1}^{4}\left[\frac{1-\lambda_{i}}{1+\lambda_{i}}\right]^{n}v_{i}v_{i}^{T}x_{0}=\left[\frac{0.9}{1.1}\right]^{n}v_{1}v_{1}^{T}x_{0}+0^{n}v_{2}v_{2}^{T}x_{0}+\left[-\frac{1}{3}\right]^{n}v_{3}v_{3}^{T}x_{0}+\left[-\frac{1}{2}\right]^{n}v_{4}v_{4}^{T}x_{0}.
\]

\end_inset

For large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, the first term obviously dominates.
\end_layout

